TOPICS COVERED (UNSUPERVISED MACHINE LEARNING & K-MEANS CLUSTERING)
Introduction to Unsupervised Machine Learning

The training session began with an introduction to Unsupervised Machine Learning, a branch of Machine Learning in which algorithms learn patterns from unlabeled data. Learned that unlike supervised learning, unsupervised learning does not use predefined target labels. Instead, the algorithm identifies hidden structures, similarities, and relationships within the data automatically.

The trainer explained that unsupervised learning is widely used for customer segmentation, recommendation systems, anomaly detection, market basket analysis, and pattern recognition.

Difference Between Supervised and Unsupervised Learning

Studied the key differences between supervised and unsupervised learning.

Learned that:

Supervised Learning uses labeled data with known target values.
Unsupervised Learning works with unlabeled data and discovers hidden patterns.
Supervised learning is mainly used for prediction, whereas unsupervised learning focuses on grouping and pattern discovery.

Compared real-world examples of both approaches to understand their applications.

Introduction to Clustering

Received an introduction to Clustering, one of the most important unsupervised learning techniques.

Learned that clustering groups similar data points together while separating dissimilar ones into different groups called clusters.

Discussed practical applications of clustering such as:

Customer Segmentation
Product Recommendation
Image Segmentation
Social Network Analysis
Document Classification
Market Research
Healthcare Data Analysis

The trainer emphasized the importance of clustering in discovering hidden patterns without prior knowledge of class labels.

Understanding K-Means Clustering

Studied K-Means Clustering, one of the most popular clustering algorithms.

Learned the working process of K-Means:

Select the number of clusters (K).
Initialize random centroids.
Assign each data point to the nearest centroid.
Update centroid positions.
Repeat the process until centroids no longer change significantly.

Understood that K-Means aims to minimize the distance between data points and their assigned cluster centroids.

Choosing the Optimal Number of Clusters

Received a detailed explanation of selecting the appropriate value of K.

Studied the Elbow Method, where different values of K are tested and the optimal cluster number is selected by observing the point where the rate of decrease in error begins to slow down.

Discussed why selecting an appropriate number of clusters improves clustering quality.

